3. Aesopeos logos: note the Latinized Greek word. Aesop’s Fables were adapted into Latin by Phaedrus, who flourished under Tiberius, so that the author's reference to such a work as an intemptatum . . . opus has given the critics difficulty. Ap- parently Seneca was ignorant of Phaedrus, or ignored him to compliment Polybius, who had shown a taste for this sort of adaptation. -hilariora studia: i.e. of light literature. —habetoz observe the force os the tense. — conroborati eius: sc. animi. — solutiora: more jovial.
